      "type": "edit",
      "id": "cb672c7c6813213f",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "cb672c7c6813213f",
        "text": "Ukraine is fighting for its existence on the battlefields of the Donbass, but Germany is just watching, conservative media and politicians grumbled in chord over the weekend. Berlin has promised Kiev flak tanks and howitzers, but for nine weeks has delivered nothing but small military equipment. Many ask: Where is the \"turnaround\" promised by Chancellor Olaf Scholz at the end of February?\n\n\"Who betrayed Ukraine? The Social Democrats!\" German Greens, leftists and liberals are now chorusing, referring to Scholz's party, with which, however, the Greens and FDP are currently forming a coalition. The strongest criticism has been coming from Eastern Europe for some time. Poles, Czechs and Balts complain about Germany's \"breach of promise\" and hold Berlin solely responsible, so to speak, for the fact that the Ukrainian army is increasingly getting into trouble in the face of Russian firepower.\n\nMany of the accusations directed at the German government are grossly exaggerated. The idea that whether Ukraine loses the war or not depends on the delivery of a few dozen German-made armored vehicles is either malicious or naive. No country except the U.S. supports Ukraine with more money than Germany, be it bilaterally or through the EU.\n\nBerlin is known to be less capable of action when it comes to military equipment. Unlike the armed forces of the United States or the United Kingdom, the Bundeswehr does not have well-stocked depots from which Ukraine could simply be supplied with ammunition and equipment for months on end. Rather, the Bundeswehr has too little of everything itself. And what it could give away - several thousand anti-tank guided missiles, for example - it has long since delivered.\n\nThe German arms industry is not much more volatile. Even discarded armored vehicles take months to be repaired. And those who now criticize Germany for not supplying battle tanks and infantry fighting vehicles from its own production forget that all other Western NATO countries have so far failed to do the same.\n\nThe accusation that Germany may not be pursuing the same war aims as other NATO allies is more accurate. Chancellor Scholz says that Ukraine must not lose the war and Russia must not win it. Many partners, on the other hand, now believe that everything must be done to ensure that Ukraine wins and Russia loses.\n\nScholz thinks this goal is dangerous, even if he does not explicitly talk about it. The chancellor apparently worries that Vladimir Putin might resort to nuclear weapons if that is the only way to prevent a humiliating defeat. The Russian warlord and his aides, in turn, miss no opportunity to warn the Germans of precisely this danger and to portray the arms deliveries from Berlin as particularly dangerous.\n\nMany Germans share Scholz's concern. Two out of three respondents recently feared an escalation that could drag Germany into the war; one in two even thought that supplying heavy weapons to Ukraine would make a nuclear war more likely. In Scholz's own party, faction and generation, the fearfulness is particularly pronounced.\n\nThe chancellor's hesitancy takes this mood into account and, from that point of view, is deliberate. But instead of saying so openly, Scholz prefers to praise himself sweepingly for his \"prudence\" and contrasts this with the attitudes of those who urge him in open letters to be even more cautious or more brash. Germany definitely does not want to lead in the war in Ukraine, at least not militarily, at least this can be clearly read from Scholz's ambiguous words.\n\nSo is Berlin deliberately delaying the delivery of heavy weapons, or are there factual reasons for the ever-new delays? Probably both are true. In any case, it is striking how much Scholz repeatedly emphasizes that he wants to avoid \"going it alone\" and, if possible, \"ride in NATO's convoy.\n\nThe fact that Germany is effectively falling behind also has to do with armaments. The promised 30 Gepard anti-aircraft tanks and the 7 self-propelled howitzers 2000 had to be repaired first. Ukrainian soldiers are currently being trained on the mobile artillery in Germany, and on the Gepard, for which ammunition had yet to be found, in July. Unlike the U.S. and other countries, the Bundeswehr does not have field howitzers that are easy to deliver and operate. For similar reasons, replacement deliveries of modern Leopard tanks to Poland, the Czech Republic or Slovakia, which have passed on their Soviet-produced tanks to Ukraine, have been delayed.\n\nWhat Scholz's government lacks most, however, is not tanks, but clear leadership and communication. Because the chancellor publicly veils rather than states his arguments and intentions, and at the same time holds together a government  Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
